The issue is:

1. A full dump is made on date A
2. We pull the dump down on date B
3. We (right now) pull all events between B-Now.

We might miss the timeframe between A-B.
Another complicating issue may be: full dump files for multiple institutions are grouped into one database object.

bibdata.title: Step through browse list generation and document for go-live

comments.body:
Current strategy:

This takes two commands. My strategy to get a total time is to do the following:

1. `time bundle exec rake browse:all`
```
real    323m45.142s
user    197m41.286s
sys     1m13.911s
```
2. `time bundle exec rake browse:load_all`
  * Note: In QA I had to run `OL_DB_PORT=5432 time bundle exec rake browse:load_all`, the port being defined is important.
  ```
103.02user 34.66system 26:29.50elapsed 8%CPU (0avgtext+0avgdata 112652maxresident)k
0inputs+10337680outputs (0major+84844minor)pagefaults 0swaps
  ```
  I'm not sure what happened here, I think this says it took 26 minutes.

Current estimate: ~ 6 hours.

then add them together. If they both go fine, and there's still time, I'll try `time /bin/bash -c "OL_DB_PORT=5432 bundle exec rake browse:all && OL_DB_PORT=5432 bundle exec rake browse:load_all"`

```
real    330m33.682s
user    202m1.801s
sys     1m50.165s
```

About 5.5 hours.

>A system upgrade this summer will replace a 20-year-old platform and provide more efficient and easier access to library resources.
